   <p class="auto-cursor-target">v2 Description: This is a notification of the creation of a document with the accompanying content.</p>
   <p>FHIR Description (<a href="http://hl7.org/implement/standards/fhir/diagnosticreport.html">Diagnostic Report</a>): <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">The findings and interpretation of diagnostic tests performed on patients, groups of patients, devices, and locations, and/or specimens derived from these. The report includes clinical context such as requesting and provider information, and some mix of atomic results, images, textual and coded interpretations, and formatted representation of diagnostic reports.</span>
   </p>
   <p>FHIR Description (<a href="http://hl7.org/implement/standards/fhir/composition.html">Composition</a>): <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">A set of healthcare-related information that is assembled together into a single logical package that provides a single coherent statement of meaning, establishes its own context and that has clinical attestation with regard to who is making the statement. <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">A Composition is the basic structure from which </span>
         <a href="http://hl7.org/implement/standards/fhir/documents.html">FHIR Documents</a>
         <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);"> - immutable bundles with attested narrative - are built.</span>
      </span>
   </p>
   <p style="margin-left: 30.0px;">
      <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">Question - is the MDM message really a document or a composition? Given that most messages will need to be Bundles anyway, is there a Bundle type other than "document" or "message" that may apply?</span>
   </p>
   <p style="margin-left: 30.0px;">
      <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">Question - is this suitable to use prior to authentication of the document? What is meant by "immutable"? Given that a composition can have a status of preliminary, it seems like a composition can be unauthenticated but is still a "frozen" snapshot of the document.</span>
   </p>
   <p>
      <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">FHIR Description (<a href="http://hl7.org/implement/standards/fhir/media.html">Media</a>):  <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">A photo, video, or audio recording acquired or used in healthcare. The actual content may be inline or provided by direct reference. </span>
      </span>
   </p>
   <p style="margin-left: 30.0px;">
      <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">
         <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">OBX segments can contain a data type of RP which may be "media".</span>
      </span>
   </p>
   <p>
      <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">
         <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">FHIR Description (<a href="http://hl7.org/implement/standards/fhir/datatypes.html#Attachment">Attachment </a>- data type): <span style="color: rgb(51,51,51);">This type is for containing or referencing attachments - additional data content defined in other formats. The most common use of this type is to include images or reports in some report format such as PDF. However, it can be used for any data that has a MIME type.</span>
         </span>
      </span>
   </p>
   <p>Also see this Zulip thread: <a href="https://chat.fhir.org/#narrow/stream/179188-v2-to.20FHIR">https://chat.fhir.org/#narrow/stream/179188-v2-to.20FHIR</a>
   </p>
